00:02:46.850 --> 00:02:49.393
But this question is specifically for X3.

00:02:50.360 --> 00:02:53.670
You move up in bands, you
wanna stay in the rep range

00:02:53.670 --> 00:02:56.280
of 15 to 40 repetitions.

00:02:56.280 --> 00:02:58.750
Now some would say that seems high.

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:02.010
Except remember in the
stronger range of motion,

00:03:02.010 --> 00:03:06.800
when you're out here, when
you're going to fatigue out here

00:03:06.800 --> 00:03:08.600
and then you diminish your range of motion

00:03:08.600 --> 00:03:10.850
then you go to fatigue here,
then you go to fatigue here.

00:03:10.850 --> 00:03:12.670
It's a much more intense stimulus

00:03:12.670 --> 00:03:16.330
and you're using more weight
than you may have ever used.

00:03:16.330 --> 00:03:19.940
With more repetitions than
you'd normally ever use.

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:22.580
Once you get past 40 repetitions,

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.410
that's the time to move to the next band.

00:03:24.410 --> 00:03:27.200
So, I hear some people go,
well I really need a band

00:03:27.200 --> 00:03:29.471
in between the two bands.

00:03:29.471 --> 00:03:31.103
(groans) I don't think you do.

00:03:32.370 --> 00:03:34.480
Because a lot of people who are following

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:39.440
